<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-02T22:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-02T22:36:00-05:00" n="1553" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1553">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/80.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Special Agent <persName type="from">Canova</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Zacatecas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-02T21:00:00-06:36">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 2, 1914, 9 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Many atrocities have been committed here by the Constitutionalists.
                                Three Christian Brothers, the President, Adrien Astruc, Professor
                                Adolphus Giles, both of them French, and Father Vega, Mexican, shot
                                June 24, 4 p.m. by order of General Chao. Fourteen others banished,
                                and now at Santa Fe, New Mexico, having been forced to make a
                                payment of $5,000 ransom. By order of the same General, 22 priests
                                Zacatecas threatened death unless they paid $100,000; and upon
                                payment they were arrested and banished, were sent to El Paso.
                                Constitutionalists’ conduct here deplorable because of multiplicity
                                of crimes.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Canova</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>